{{other people}} {{Infobox Politician |name = Thomas Dyer |image = Thomasdyer.jpg |birth_date = {{birth date|1805|1|13}} |birth_place = Canton, [[Connecticut]] |death_date = {{death date and age|1862|6|6|1805|1|13}} |death_place = [[Connecticut]], United States |residence = Chicago, [[Illinois]] |office = Mayor of Chicago |order = 18th |term_start = 1856 |term_end = 1857 |predecessor = [[Levi Boone]] |successor = [[John Wentworth (Illinois)|John Wentworth]] |party = [[United States Democratic Party|Democratic]] |religion = |spouse = |children = |website = }}
'''Thomas Dyer''' (January 13, 1805{{spaced ndash}}June 6, 1862; buried in [[Connecticut]]) served as mayor of Chicago, [[Illinois]] (1856–1857) for the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]]. He also served as the founding president of the [[Chicago Board of Trade]].
He was a former meat-packing partner of former mayor [[John Putnam Chapin]], who was one of Chicago's first [[Meat packers|meat packers]]. Chapin built a [[slaughterhouse]] on the South Branch of the [[Chicago River]] in 1844.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Group|first1=Genealogy Trails History|title=The History of Chicago's Mayors - presented by Illinois Genealogy Trails|url=http://www.genealogytrails.com/ill/cook/chicagomayors.html|website=www.genealogytrails.com|accessdate=26 January 2018}}</ref>
